            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> Literally “sold subject to release” (i.e. from the sale, conditional on repayment of the loan). In effect the house is security for the loan and the marker serves the purpose of advertising that the property is encumbered. On the terminology of security transactions see E. M. Harris, <i>CQ</i> 38, 1988, 351-81; and the discussion in P. Millett, <a class="highlight" href="https://www.repository.cam.ac.uk/handle/1810/245064"> "M. I. Finley's <i>Studies in Ancient Athenian Land and Credit</i> Reconsidered"</a>. This one is unusual in being dated.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> The ca. 300 surviving markers (<i>horoi</i>) of property subject to security transactions in Attica show loans being made both by individuals and, less commonly, collectives, including demes (cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2761"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2761</a> deme Halai, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AgoraXIX/h92"><i>Agora</i> XIX H92</a> deme Kerameis, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2670"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2670</a> deme Phlya, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/63156"><i>SEG</i> 63.156</a> deme Myrrhinous). On loans by demes in general, see D. Whitehead, <i>Demes of Attica</i>, 1986, 158-60 (rightly sceptical about the attempt of M. I. Finley to belittle the significance of deme loans).</br></br>

Around 1-4 markers of loans respectively by demes, phratries, genē, and tribes are extant (C. A. Thomsen, <i>GRBS</i> 55, 2015, 154-75 at 165 n. 31 = <i>SEG</i> 65.2). A much larger number (ca. 22, Thomsen, 154) record loans by <i>eranistai</i>, a term denoting an association formed on the basis of contributions from members (cf. English “friendly society”. Aristotle, <i>EN</i> 1160a 19-20 gives thiasoi and groups of <i>eranistai</i> as examples of associations formed for pleasure, i.e. sacrifice and social intercourse). Sometimes these associations were formed ad hoc for the purpose of a loan, and this is demonstrably the case with <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/2721"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2721</a>. The relatively large number of extant markers of loans by <i>eranistai</i> in comparison with other types of association suggest that the other <i>eranistai</i> recorded by these markers were also mostly of this ad hoc type, though some of them may have been more permanent associations (cf. Thomsen). For dedications by <i>eranistai</i> see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/634"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 634</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/640">640</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/649">649</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/654">654</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/655">655</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/661">661</a>.</span>
            </div>
            

